Nice clash, but it's not reverse-engineerable enough for Reverse mode. I ended up winning mine with 75%, while 2nd got 25% and the rest got 0%.

I actually solved the problem and guessed the condition after a long time struggling, but accidentally left a mistake from one of my older attempts in my code (limiting the output to 18, which only caused an issue on validator 4). It is a bit too complicated for Reverse to guess that you stop on "z" or a second "a", imo.

Goal
* There are no numbers to print. Please rewrite as follows:

Print a string of letters starting from {{a}}, going up in intervals of [[I]] (being the number of letters to skip), and wrapping around to {{a}} after {{z}}. Continue this up to the point where {{z}} or another {{a}} is reached.

Input
* Please change "skipped spaces to z or a" to "letters to skip".

Output
* Please delete everything and revise as follows:

<<? lines:>> A string of letters starting from {{a}}, one letter per line.

Cases
* Test 1: Please delete the extra newline at the end of the output.

Thanks.
